reviews.headline: The only blush to survive!
reviews.comments:
My face eats blush. I dont know why. I am 42 and its been eating blush my entire makeup wearing life. I have tried all the best-reviewed, most pigmented, allegedly "longest lasting" blushes on the market and they've all disappeared before i even arrive at work. I'm very fair, so no blush = a day of "are you getting sick" type comments.

I picked this up on a recommendation from Ulta staff member who watched me swatch nearly every blush in store. The limited range of shades made me pass this over a dozen times. But it turns out that Blind Date is my perfect every day, neutral and easy to wear dream shade. 

I can put this stuff on (cream first, set with the powder) at 5:30 am, and it still looks fantastic for a 5:30 pm dinner date. I even live in a miserably hot and humid environment and sweat a lot with my work, and this stuff hangs on even when my foundation, eyeliner, lipstick and everything else has failed. I like using the highlighter shade as a countouring eyeshadow also for a monochromatic look! 10/10! Morphe, bring out more shades so i can buy more!

reviews.headline: These Beat High End
reviews.comments: Forget Patrick Ta and One Size, These are it girl! The price is on point, the finishes are beautiful and they are pigmented but not too much. The cream blush has the most beautiful finish and is an excellent finisher. The packaging and large mirror are definitely a bonus.

faceoff_positive.comments:
Okay, let's talk about Morphe Cheek Thrills in Blind Date‚Äîbecause this little trio is giving options! You get a cream, a balm, and a powder, all in a gorgeous, neutral mid-tone pink that just works. Whether you're into a soft, dewy flush or a bold, sculpted cheek, this compact has your back. It's definitely in the same league as the One Size Blush Trio and the Patrick Ta Blush Duos, offering that same mix-and-match versatility.

The pros: First, the pigment is intense. No wimpy, barely-there color here. All three formulas pack a serious punch, so a little goes a long way. The layering is magic. The cream and powder together? Chef's kiss. The cream gives a smooth, seamless base, and the powder locks it in for all-day wear. The shade Blind Date is super versatile. It's that perfect fresh, natural pink that looks like you just came in from the cold (but, like, in a cute way‚Äîit's giving Sabrina Carpenter). It works with so many looks. There's also multi-use potential. The balm could double as a glossy highlighter, and the cream would make a stunning monochromatic lip. It works for different skin types‚Äîpowder for oily babes, cream and balm for dry skin, or mix and match depending on your mood. Plus, the packaging looks high-end, includes a mirror, and has a cover for the cream and balm sections to keep everything neat and clean.

Now for the cons. The balm can be a little patchy. It's got that glossy, skin-like vibe, but it doesn't always blend as smoothly as the other two. A little extra finesse or a damp sponge might help. It's also super pigmented. This isn't a "mindlessly slap it on" blush. If you go in heavy-handed, you'll be blending for a while, so start light and build up.

Final thoughts? If you love trying different textures and customizing your blush look, this is such a fun product to play with. The cream and powder are the real MVPs‚Äîthey melt into the skin beautifully and last all day. The balm is a little trickier, but it can still work if you're into that fresh, dewy glow. Overall, Blind Date is a gorgeous, flattering pink that's easy to dress up or down. Just go in with a light hand, and you'll be obsessed.
faceoff_positive.headline: Triple Threat

faceoff_negative.comments:
I recently tried the Morphe Cheek Thrills Multi-Finish Face Trio Blush, and while I had high hopes, I found the product to be just okay. The color payoff is nice, with a pretty mix of matte, shimmer, and satin finishes, which allows for some versatility in your blush application. The shades are flattering and have the potential to create a gorgeous, natural flush.

However, my biggest issue with this product was the blending. Unfortunately, I found it difficult to blend the blush seamlessly into my skin. It tended to sit on top of my face rather than melt in, leaving harsh lines. This made it challenging to achieve that soft, airbrushed look that I usually prefer. It wasn't a dealbreaker, but it definitely impacted my overall experience.

While the packaging is sleek and the product itself has potential, I think the formula could be improved for better blend-ability. If you don't mind a little extra effort in blending, this could still work for you. But for me, it just didn't live up to my expectations.
faceoff_negative.headline: It's an ok product
